This was fantastic. We eat a lot of Indian food at our house, and this was as good as some of my favorites. It's very creamy, not spicy, and just a little sour, which I didn't think I would like but really enjoyed. This is a nice counter-point to those bright yellow highly spiced bitter curries. This would be a good choice to add to a formal Indian menu with many different foods served. We ate it with homemade naan, cumin rice, and spicy zucchini, tomatoes and chick peas. I made a couple of minor changes: took the advice of other reviewers and subbed light coconut milk for 3/4 of the whole milk (I had some left over from another Indian feast), don't like huge chunks of meat in curries, so cut my beef into 1/2 inch cubes, didn't have whole spices, and so just eyeballed ground cloves and cinnamon and used ground cayenne pepper. Also used one can of Muir Glenn fire-roasted tomatoes instead of fresh tomatoes.Lastly, I thought the recipe was a tad sour, so I added two pinches of sugar. Next time I'll probably use only two Tbsp. of lemon juice. Recipe takes a while to make, but it's mostly simmering time. Recipe makes terrific leftovers (I'm eating them for lunch as I type).

