Rating: 0
To the cook from Montara, CA.....yes its an Indian recipe...or almost an Indian recipe for beef. India has one of the largest Muslim populations in the world and beef is eaten all over the country. It is also cooked by the catholic community.It is cheaper then chicken and mutton (goat meat) and hence is also consumed by the poor in many parts of the country. One very BIG FLAW in this recipe ( Besides the major grey chutney and the whole milk)is the use of the bay leaf. Indian cuisine uses "Tejpatta", often mistakenly called the "Indian bay leaf". The 2 are botanically completely different plants. The bay leaf is used in the European and mediterranean cuisines. The leaves are large and leathery. The Indian tejpatta are smaller leaves and the dried leaves are very brittle. They are leaves of a cassia plant and have a flavor similar to the cinnamon bark. If u cant get tejpatta (very easily available in Indian groceries)...leave it out completely or use a piece of cinnamon bark. Also...if u are planning on adding coconut milk to the dish....this is how it is traditionally done. The coconut milk is always extracted fresh and is added in 2 additions to a dish. Initially the second or thinner extract is added and the dish is cooked. The thicker/ first extract is added at the end when the food is completely cooked. This thick extract adds a rich coconut flavor to the dish and is just warmed through. If it is added while cooking, it tends to curdle and releases coconut oil into the dish making it very greasy.For the thinner extract mix 1/2 cup of canned milk with 1/2 cup of water. For the first extract use canned coconut milk directly without diluting. Also try and get the lite coconut milk. The full fat kind is too rich....the fresh extract made at home is not as thick.

